<TEXT>
bourhane was repairing his radio christmas day 
when the chinese crowds came 
down with black devils they shouted black devils go 
home the chants echoed off the walls of his dormitory at the 
nanking polytechnical institute 
i thought they wanted to kill me kill all of us from africa 
said the 23yearold student from the african country of comoros 
who uses one name i started pacing the room my sweat was cold 
for the next four days thousands of chinese youths marched 
through nankings streets shouting racist slogans and calling for 
the punishment of african students who brawled with chinese at a 
dance when the chinese objected to the africans bringing chinese 
women 
the racial incidents which began in nanking at the christmas eve 
dance and spread to three other cities were fueled by a mixture of 
racism and political restiveness chinese youths wanted to express 
anger and frustration africans were an easy target 
in hangzhou africans boycotted classes because they said 
university operators were telling chinese that all africans have 
aids in the central city of wuhan chinese youths threw rocks at 
foreign students dormitories and in beijing africans at one 
college stopped going to class after chinese protested an alleged 
assault by a black man on a chinese woman 
african students have been coming to china since 1959 as part of 
beijings policy of asserting a role of leadership in the third 
world today about 1500 african students a year receive chinese 
scholarships 
but africanchinese relations are strained many chinese are open 
about their disdain toward black people 
when i look at their black faces i feel uncomfortable a 
25yearold said during a demonstration in nanking when i see 
them with our women my heart boils 
most chinese have little or no contact with different races or 
cultures so a foreign face naturally draws attention but africans 
say the chinese treat whites and other asians better 
not a day goes by when im not insulted said billy sissoko 
a student from mali today someone looked at my skin and asked me 
after six years in china why havent you become whiter 
chinese often say they find dark skin ugly because it implies 
that a person engages in manual labor still not a glorious calling 
in this dictatorship of the working class 
black gods in chinese mythology are invariably wicked black 
children is the name given to unplanned children 
chinese also look down on those poorer than themselves and many 
african nations fall into that category 
this feeling of superiority turns to resentment when chinese 
discover that african students in china receive about 10 times the 
monthly stipend of about 6 given chinese students 
add the issue of women to this mixture of economic and cultural 
prejudice and the situation becomes explosive 
most african students in china are men sent here for as long as 
six years they say it is only natural they should mix with the 
local women many chinese object 
one night sun min a 20yearold woman in nanking invited an 
african man and a white american woman to dinner later she said 
her neighbors gossiped you had a foreigner to dinner thats not 
bad but how could you also invite a black man 
the chinese government insists racism does not exist in china and 
that it played no part in the recent confrontations 
the official xinhua news agency blamed the clashes in nanking on 
a group of africans and said chinese demonstrators who shouted 
erroneous slogans were immediately stopped 
xinhua also accused the associated press the voice of america 
and agence francepresse of distorting the incidents by reporting 
the racist elements in the clashes 
by the third day of demonstrations in nanking protesters had 
turned their wrath from the africans to the chinese government a 
main concern was that africans should not receive special treatment 
under chinese law 
in effect students used the demonstrations to attack special 
privileges given to foreigners the christmas eve clash gave them 
an excuse to address a sensitive political issue without confronting 
it directly 
it doesnt matter if youre a foreigner or deng xiaopings son 
if you break the law you must be punished said one chinese 
student in nanking thats why i am marching 
chinese students who marched in beijing last tuesday echoed the 
call 
we are chinese and we feel the law isnt protecting us one 
woman said what good is the law then 
african students say the only way to change chinese attitudes 
toward blacks is through education 
but these people dont want to learn about africa said tchek 
baisa a student from zaire they dont need us anymore 
indeed chinese foreign policy has changed since the 1960s and 
70s when third world solidarity was a central priority now 
chinas main focus is on western trade and investment 
in nanking bourhane said he didnt think much would change 
really i just want to go home before things become too much 
worse he said 
</TEXT>
