<TEXT>
britain has been convinced since 1987 that libya is 
building a plant to produce chemical weapons and first alerted the 
united states to its concerns 18 months ago the sunday times of 
london reported 
the newspaper quoting what it called wellplaced sources said a 
long and intensive british intelligence operation included detailed 
monitoring of the shipment of materials from european and japanese 
factories to libya 
in a separate investigation following the british tip the 
americans had reached the same conclusion the newspaper said 
britain was the first country to support us allegations that 
libya is building a factory to produce chemical weapons near rabta 
60 miles south of tripoli libya maintains the factory will produce 
pharmaceuticals 
the foreign office said wednesday it had independent information 
about the plants purpose but would not say what it was 
the sunday times quoted unnamed american sources as saying both 
the united states and britain had been trying for more than three 
years to persuade allied governments principally west germany 
italy and japan to stop private firms from supplying libya with raw 
materials and technology required to build the plant 
apart from a degree of japanese cooperation in identifying the 
foreign companies working for libyan leader col moammar gadhafi 
the effort failed the newspaper said 
the observer another weekly london newspaper reported that the 
man responsible for building and equipping the libyan plant is dr 
ihsen barbouti an iraqi citizen living in london and operating 
through a string of small firms in several countries 
it said barboutis companies in switzerland west germany and 
libya have been responsible for the civil engineering at the complex 
however it said the observer has no reason to believe that dr 
barbouti was aware of what the us claims to be the purpose of the 
