<DOCNO> AP890108-0093 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the rules of the corporate name game could change 
drastically if toyota motor corp loses its struggle to hang onto 
lexus as the name for its forthcoming line of luxury cars 
if a federal appeals court bars toyota from using lexus because 
of trademark infringement the precedent might vastly complicate the 
already brainbusting job of choosing new names 
its a humdinger isnt it said jerome gilson a chicago 
lawyer who helped prepare the report that formed the basis for last 
years federal trademark law revisions 
when japans biggest manufacturer ran afoul of mead corps lexis 
trademark it was only the latest corporate giant to be snagged by a 
smaller company with a prior mark 
among previous victims usx corp general motor corps saturn 
division and nbc whose shortlived n logo happened to be the 
same as that of the nebraska educational television network 
even the italian gun maker beretta has gotten into the act suing 
gms chevrolet division over using the beretta name for a sporty 
compact coupe the suit is pending 
the lexuslexis decision could be bigger than any of them 
though thats because us district judge david n edelstein went 
unusually far in siding with the holder of an existing trademark 
an affirmation by the 2nd us circuit court of appeals which 
will hear the case jan 30 would have national repercussions 
because of the prestige of the panel which is one notch below the 
us supreme court 
toyota is allowed to use lexus at auto shows but not in national 
advertising until the appeal is heard the line is scheduled to go 
on sale in september 
a loss for toyota would be disastrous edelstein said toyota had 
to either drop the lexus name or among other things put a 
disclaimer in all its advertising saying lexus was not related to 
lexis 
even beyond toyotas difficulties the worldwide stakes in 
trademark battles are enormous the dollar value of famous names 
explains the wars for control of companies such as rjr nabisco inc 
which owns names like oreo ritz winston and hawaiian puch 
toyota was given a judo flip by mead a dayton ohiobased 
company that owns a computer dataretrieval service called lexis 
that is used mainly by lawyers journalists and researchers 
mead failed to prove confusion was an issue clearly no one who 
wants the lexis computer service would mistakenly stumble into a 
lexus showroom and buy a luxury car 
rather mead succeeded under a new york state law that protects 
trademarks from dilution it said toyotas lexus would become so 
wellknown that potential lexis customers would think of the car 
first when they heard the word lexis ergo dilution 
the idea that a trademark can be diluted is a departure from the 
main tradition of trademark law which protected trademarks only 
when there was clear potential for confusion between two products 
more than 20 other states have antidilution statutes including 
california illinois and massachusetts like new yorks those have 
usually been given weak interpretations by the courts but as long 
as they are on the books they can be enforced 
new yorks 35yearold antidilution law was a ticking time 
bomb that went off with edelsteins ruling said gilson the 
trademark expert 
the us trademark association tried to defuse the states legal 
bombs last year by proposing a federal antidilution provision that 
would supercede state laws and protect only truly famous trademarks 
on the order of tiffany and yves st laurent lexis most likely 
would not have made the cut 
the provision was rejected because congress didnt want to 
tinker with the state system said william borchard counsel to 
the us trademark association 
striking a blow for the little guy edelstein said lesserknown 
but distinctive trademarks deserve as much protection as the famous 
names owned by the largest and most powerful corporations in the 
country 
the problem with protecting all trademarks equally no matter how 
obscure is that soon in fact now no good names will be 
available for companies that need them 
in a typical recent debacle hnginternorth inc switched its 
name to enteron upon the advice of lippincott amp margulies only to 
discover it was a name for the human alimentary canal it settled 
for enron 
meads own nexis service a sibling of lexis shares its name 
with at least a dozen other products including a haircare line 
called nexxus 
clive chajet chairman of lippincott amp margulies which worked 
with toyota but did not pick lexus said mead should stop 
complaining 
if i were mead i would send a thankyou note to mr eiji 
toyoda the chairman for raising the awareness level of my 
product chajet said 
</TEXT>
